tyle="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/3LN7bJ9</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Mrunkn0w1]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Robin Hood meme pop-up card (first concept)</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/2sRSSHe</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/C5967Du.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>I’m working on this new meme card. One of my favorites. This is a really rough first try. I’m now working on the final artwork, and the branch in the foreground will also look much better. Based on the Rhys Darby - Robin Hood - Fight For Fair 2 degrees advertisement</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/2sRSSHe</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[PaulDeGraaf]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>The One-legged Torii of Nagasaki</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/CmtMFmv</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/SaW5MEQ.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>被爆 - Hibaku - literally translates as "one affected by an explosion/bombing." 

The most common modern usage is "hibakusha" which refers to individual people who experienced, survived, or who suffered physical effects from the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki. The word itself has nothing to do with a new type of bomb, the unique designs of the bombs, or even the radiological aspects of the bombs. I found myself hung up on this nomenclature and eventually needed a teacher of english to fully understand:

 "Compare, in American English, 9/11. They're just two numbers. Even if we interpret it as a date, there have been hundreds of September 11ths in US history, and countless events have occurred during them. Nothing in the etymology of this term refers directly to the destruction of the World Trade Center and the resulting deaths. But that's the term that caught on."

This was a facet of language I rarely think about; how the meaning of the word depends wholly upon background historical knowledge and cultural context.

There are also hibaku buildings and, something I found personally interesting, hibaku trees. 

This is the One-legged Torii Gate in Nagasaki. It was one of several torii for the Shinto Sannō Shrine, originally built in 1638, whose name means "King of the Mountain." On August 9, 1945, the first 20-kiloton Mark III nuclear bomb (whose plutonium core was created in Hanford, Washington) detonated 2,600 feet away. The shrine was instantly flattened, and the force of the shock wave smashed the torii gate. One half of the gate shattered and fell, but the other half rotated about thirty degrees on its pedestal and astonishingly remained upright.

Today the dense urban regrowth of Nagasaki largely obscures this hibaku structure. It is a landmark that will not be found except by those who seek it, standing atop a staircase at the end of a dead-end street, at the start of a residential area connected by tight mazes of pedestrian-only streets. The remains of the shattered half of the gate lie nearby with informational displays. The base is covered with gifts and offerings. The shrine itself has been rebuilt, just around the corner from the gate. It is the site of a kindergarten playground, which is itself sheltered beneath the massive canopy of two great Camphor trees who are assessed to be 500 years old and are themselves... hibaku.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/06kRSVM.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Koy7zSc.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/AZdc1n1.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/CmtMFmv</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[AtomicAerials]]></dc:creator></item></channel></rss>